<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25079b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25079b">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25079b"> 79(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> longevity boards</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">China is full of examples. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> &lsquo;Coffins&rsquo; are tabooed under the term &lsquo;<mark>longevity boards</mark>.&rsquo; Mr. Giles says that &lsquo;boards of old age,&rsquo; and &lsquo;clothes of old age sold here,&rsquo; are common shop-signs in every Chinese city; death and burial being always, if possible, spoken of euphemistically in some such terms as these. <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECTTT" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ECTTT"><cite title="source">Tom Tit Tot</cite></a> (1898) 134</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14047k" href="c14all.htm#c14047k">VI.C.14:047(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
